<p>For immediate release</p>
<p style="text-align: right;">Contact:<br />
Steve Barkan<br />
steve@sgacamp.com<br />
(626) 535-9616 x2<br />
(323) 533-3106</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Chevron Oil, one of the most aggressive opponents of global warming legislation, launched a campaign to help Gil Cedillo get elected to the Los Angeles City Council late Tuesday night and early Wednesday morning. Chevron is spending its money through the so-called L.A. Jobs PAC, a committee of the L.A. Area Chamber of Commerce.</p>
<p>The Chevron-backed committee filed an Independent Expenditure report yesterday with an illegible legally-required identification disclaimer. However, a photograph of the actual signs distributed throughout the district, the financial sources included âMajor funding provided by Farmers Underwriters Association and Chevron Corporation in the Amount of $80,000.â</p>
<p>Cedillo and Chevron have a long and deep financial relationship.</p>
<p style="padding-left: 30px;">â¢ Chevron contributed more than $11,000 to Cedillo while he was in the Legislature in Sacramento.</p>
<p style="padding-left: 60px;">$3,900 to Cedillo on 8/18/10<br />
$3,900 to Cedillo on 5/24/10<br />
$1,000 to Cedillo on 9/6/07<br />
$1,000 to Cedillo on 4/15/05<br />
$1,000 to Cedillo on 8/29/02<br />
$750 to Cedillo on 5/2/00<br />
$11,550 Total in direct contributions</p>
<p style="padding-left: 30px;">â¢ Chevronâs contributions to Cedillo increased steeply after he refused to vote for AB 32, the groundbreaking law to control pollution that causes global warming, and SB 1762, another global warming bill. Chevron spent $1.8 million on lobbying to defeat or water down AB 32 and other legislation that year alone.</p>
<p style="padding-left: 30px;">â¢ Shortly thereafter, Cedillo chaired the California Latino Legislative Caucus, and under his leadership the Caucus reversed its policy of disclosing donors to its affiliated non-profit. Chevron was a major donor.Â (seeÂ <a href="http://josegardea2013.com/home/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/Gil-Cedillo_Latino-Caucus.pdf">attached article</a>)</p>
<p>Chevron has boasted record profits in recent years as gas prices have risen, and even reported $7 billion in profit last quarter despite being forced to pay a record safety violation fine for the Richmond refinery explosion.</p>
<p>As a State Senator in Sacramento, Cedillo compiled the 2nd worst environmental voting record of any Democrat in the Senate in 2006, the year he refused to support AB 32.</p>
<p>âThat may be the way Gil Cedillo operated in Sacramento,â said Jose Gardea, the local candidate for the 1st Council District. âBut we donât sell out our health, safety and the environment to the oil companies here,â Gardea concluded.</p>
<p>The complete disclaimer on the signs distributed reads âPaid for by LA Jobs PAC: Sponsored by the Los Angeles Chamber of Commerce. 350 Bixel St., Major funding provided by Farmers Underwriters Association and Chevron Corporation in the Amount of $80,000.â</p>
<p>The election is on Tuesday, March 5th. The 1st District includes Highland Park, Lincoln Heights, Mount Washington, Cypress Park, Glassell Park, Chinatown, Pico-Union, Westlake, Angelino Heights, Echo Park, North University Park, Koreatown, Montecito Heights and MacArthur Park.</p>
<p>Gardea is supported by Councilmembers Ed Reyes and Jose Huizar, Assemblymember Jimmy Gomez and hundreds of local neighborhood leaders.</p>
